h3. Issue Summary

Custom icons for Connect apps don't work. 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create an app ([https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/bitbucket/getting-started/])
 # Add a repoPage and specify the icon:

{code:java}
"icon": {
    "url": "/icon.png"
}{code}

 # Install the app
 # Navigate to a repository to see the repoPage.

h3. Expected Results

The icon should be the custom icon.
h3. Actual Results

The icon is the default icon.
h3. Workaround

There are a limited number of icons [here|[https://docs.atlassian.com/aui/7.9.3/docs/icons.html]] that can be specified under "params" for a module. For example: 
{code:java}
"params": {
    "auiIcon": "aui-iconfont-discover"
}{code}
This isn't a perfect workaround, since you still can't set any image for the icon, but it's a bit more customizable than the default icon.

The documentation when you update Branching Model Settings via API 2.0 states that using the *use_mainbranch* field, the field *name* must be null or *not provided*.
{panel}
*use_mainbranch* _boolean_
 Indicates if the setting points at an explicit branch (false) or tracks the main branch (true). When true the _name_ must be null or not provided. When false the name must contain a non-empty branch name.
{panel}
However, the *name* field description states that: _It must be null when use_mainbranch is true. Otherwise it must be a non-empty value._
{panel}
*name* _string_
 The configured branch. It must be null when use_mainbranch is true. Otherwise it must be a non-empty value. It is possible for the configured branch to not exist (e.g. it was deleted after the settings are set). In this case is_valid will be false. The branch must exist when updating/setting the name or an error will occur.
{panel}
I believe the descriptions are contracting with each other because when we run the API 2.0 endpoint, it is required to pass the *name* field if the field *use_mainbranch* is set to true.

E.g:
{code:java}
{"development": {"use_mainbranch": true, "name": null}}
{code}
*Documentation*: [https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Bworkspace%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/branching-model/settings]

*Feature request:* 
 It would be awesome to clearly state that *name* is required when *use_mainbranch* is set to true.

The feature request here would be to have a button to download the git log of the repository, having the option to add or remove flags to get the history of commits. 

It would be something similar than the command below:

{code}
git log --graph --pretty --oneline
{code}

The idea here would be to download this information in a text file so the users wouldn't need to go to the terminal to do that.

h3. Issue Summary
When attempting to create a Branch through Jira, if any branch other than the main branch is selected, the newly created branch will still have the main branch as its destination branch.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
1. Have a Bitbucket + Jira integration correctly set up;
2. Navigate to Jira, and open any issue or create a new one if you have no issues to look at;
3. On the issues page, click on create branch;
4. On the "From Branch" box, select anything other than the main branch;
5. Create the branch;
6. You will see that the main branch will be selected as the destination branch;

h3. Expected Results
The selected branch in the "From Branch" dropdown should be the destination branch of the newly created branch.

h3. Actual Results
The main branch is always the destination branch of branches created in Jira.

h3. Workaround
Manually set the destination branch after creation in Bitbucket Cloud by navigating to the respective branch page > change destination.

From an API perspective, when the user makes a call to a repository where they do not have access to, it will return:
{code} Access denied. You must have write or admin access.{code}

On the other hand, when the user accesses a repository which does not exist, it will return:
{code}> {"type": "error", "error": {"message": "Repository adrian_matellanes/this-repo-not-exist not found"}}{code}

A person could potentially guess the name of the repository for an account which they do not have access to and verify if the repository exists from the error message. 

The suggested approach will be to have a generic error be returned instead to prevent this from happening.

Github has the facility to upload Maven-like Java packages to it, giving others the opportunity to import and use our code by simply adding the following to their POM or Gradle files:

{{<dependency>}}
{{  <groupId>com.my.group</groupId>}}
{{  <artifactId>special-project</artifactId>}}
{{  <version>1.2.3</version>}}
{{</dependency>}}

Does Bitbucket have, or plan to have, this type of functionality?
